{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1bfdf06f-37c9-4840-968a-6b4e21012198","content":"The working directory is empty, so I'll provide guidance based on the **skill-validator evaluation format** used for MCP skill plugins.\n\n## Format: `evaluation.yml`\n\nYour evaluations go in an `evaluation.yml` file with this structure:\n\n```yaml\nevaluations:\n  - id: search-by-category\n    description: \"Find products in the Electronics category\"\n    prompt: \"What electronics do you have in stock?\"\n    expected_tool_calls:\n      - tool: search_products\n        arguments:\n          category: \"Electronics\"\n    expected_response_contains:\n      - \"Electronics\"\n\n  - id: price-filter\n    description: \"Filter products by price range\"\n    prompt: \"Show me items under $50\"\n    expected_tool_calls:\n      - tool: search_products\n        arguments:\n          max_price: 50\n```\n\n## What Makes a Good Evaluation Question\n\n1. **Clear intent** — The prompt should unambiguously map to specific tool(s) and parameters.\n2. **Varied complexity** — Include single-tool calls, multi-step chains, and queries requiring parameter inference.\n3. **Edge cases** — Ambiguous inputs, missing info, empty results, invalid filters.\n4. **Natural phrasing** — Use how a real user would ask, not how the API is structured.\n\n**Good examples for a product catalog:**\n- Simple lookup: *\"Find the price of Widget X\"*\n- Multi-param: *\"Show red shoes under $100 in size 9\"*\n- Multi-step: *\"Compare the top-rated laptop with the cheapest one\"*\n- Ambiguous: *\"What's popular right now?\"* (tests whether the LLM picks a reasonable default)\n\n**Avoid:**\n- Prompts that mirror the tool signature verbatim (too easy)\n- Questions with no correct tool to call (unless testing refusal)\n\nWould you like me to scaffold out a full `evaluation.yml` for your product catalog server?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab7e0532-f113-4b52-bc32-dc85a4e8dcf0","reasoningOpaque":"","reason